    description: 'Environmental justice litigation challenges the documented pattern by which environmental harms — industrial pollution, hazardous waste facilities, contaminated water supplies, and toxic air emissions — are disproportionately concentrated in low-income communities and communities of color, whose residents lack the political and economic resources to resist the siting decisions that impose these burdens on them. The Cancer Alley corridor along the Mississippi River between New Orleans and Baton Rouge, home to dozens of petrochemical plants and some of the highest cancer rates in the nation, has become a focal point for litigation that combines Title VI civil rights complaints to the EPA, state court nuisance actions, and federal constitutional equal protection claims. Proving discriminatory intent — as opposed to disparate impact — is a formidable legal hurdle that has limited the success of some claims, driving advocates toward Title VI administrative remedies and the growing body of state environmental justice statutes that require agencies to consider cumulative impacts in permitting decisions. These cases matter because they represent the intersection of civil rights and environmental law, and their outcomes determine whether the promise of equal protection extends to protection from the physical environment in which people live, work, and raise their children.',
