    category: 'Foundational',
    description: 'Court hierarchy and jurisdiction describe the structured, multi-tiered architecture of the American judicial system — a system in which trial courts first find the facts and apply the law, intermediate appellate courts review those decisions for legal error, and courts of last resort (supreme courts) resolve the most consequential and contested legal questions with finality and binding authority. The United States operates two parallel court systems — a federal system created by Article III of the Constitution and the fifty separate state systems — each with its own trial courts, intermediate appellate courts, and supreme court, though the U.S. Supreme Court sits atop both systems as the final arbiter of federal and constitutional law. Jurisdiction is the threshold question in every lawsuit: a court must have both subject-matter jurisdiction (authority over the type of dispute) and personal jurisdiction (authority over the parties) before it can adjudicate a case, and a judgment entered without either is void. Understanding how a case travels upward through the hierarchy — from trial court through discretionary review in a supreme court that grants certiorari to fewer than two percent of petitions — is essential to predicting where litigation will be fought and how far it can go.',
